'''Yahagi Shrine''' (やはぎじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Minamihonmachi, {{ill|lt=Yao|Q490872|WD=Q490872|1=Yao, Osaka}}, {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|WD=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former rank in the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

It is also called "'''Betsugū Hachiman'''," and "Yahagi" is also read as "Yatsukuri."

=== Overview ===
This area is said to have originally been the residence site of the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yahagi no Muraji|1=UNKNOWN}}, a collateral branch of the {{ill|lt=Mononobe clan|Q1755836|WD=Q1755836|1=Mononobe clan}}, and the shrine is their tutelary shrine.

In the 11th century it became a Kamo-betsugū (Yao Kamo-betsugū) of {{ill|lt=Iwashimizu Hachiman-gū|Q710098|WD=Q710098|1=Iwashimizu Hachimangū}}, and in the Edo period it performed Kamo service duties for Iwashimizu Hachiman-gū. This is why it is called Betsugū Hachiman.

Several large {{ill|lt=camphor trees|Q158722|WD=Q158722|1=Camphora officinarum}} grow in the precincts. In addition, a large {{ill|lt=ginkgo|Q43284|WD=Q43284|lt=ichō|1=Ginkgo biloba}} tree in front of the shrine has many breast-like protrusions on its trunk, and there is a folk belief that decocting and drinking this bark increases breast milk.

The shrine preserves a "{{ill|lt=sankakubuchi shinju-kyō|Q11357232|WD=Q11357232|1=Triangular-Rimmed Divine Beast Mirror}}" mirror said to have been excavated from the precincts, designated a Yao City tangible cultural property.

